'''Leonid Mitrofanovich Zamyatin''' ({{lang-ru|Леонид Митрофанович Замятин}}) (born 9 March 1922) is a former [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] [[ambassador]] and [[diplomat]].<ref name=kommersant>{{cite web|url=http://www.kommersant.com/p572821/r_1/%E2%80%9CThatcher_had_a_Definite_Womanish_Feeling_towards_Gorbachev%E2%80%9D/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303212355/http://www.kommersant.com/p572821/r_1/%E2%80%9CThatcher_had_a_Definite_Womanish_Feeling_towards_Gorbachev%E2%80%9D/|archive-date=3 March 2016|title=Thatcher had a Definite Womanish Feeling towards Gorbachev|work=[[Kommersant]]|date=4 May 2005}} Interview with Zamyatin by Marina Kalashnikova.</ref> He graduated from the [[Moscow Aviation Institute]], and worked as a diplomat from 1946.<ref name=kommersant/> He became an adviser to the Soviet delegation at the United Nations, and a permanent representative of the Soviet Union on the [[International Atomic Energy Agency|IAEA]] [[Board of Governors of the International Atomic Energy Agency|Board of Governors]].<ref name=kommersant/> From 1962 to 1970, he served in the [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Russia|Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the Soviet Union]], becoming head of the press department.<ref name=kommersant/> From 1970 to 1978, he was director general of [[Telegraph Agency of the Soviet Union|TASS]], the official news agency of the [[Soviet Union]].<ref name=kommersant/> He was Chairman of the International Information Department of the [[Central Committee of the Communist Party of the Soviet Union|Central Committee]] of the [[Communist Party of the Soviet Union]] from 1978 to 1986.<ref name=kommersant/><ref>{{Cite news |first=Craig R. |last= Whitney|title= Soviet Envoy Who Knows How to Please|url= https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=950DE4DC1431F935A35757C0A96F948260&sec=&spon=|work=The New York Times |date= 6 April 1989|accessdate=24 August 2017}}</ref> In 1986, he was appointed the Soviet ambassador to the United Kingdom. He was forced to resign his ambassadorship after his refusal to condemn the [[1991 Soviet coup d'état attempt|1991 August Coup]] against [[Mikhail Gorbachev]].<ref>{{Cite news |agency=[[Associated Press]]|title=Soviet Turmoil: Moscow Calls 6 Envoys Home|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9D0CE1DA1431F934A3575AC0A967958260|work=The New York Times |date=7 September 1991|accessdate=24 August 2017}}</ref>

